# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: avid-technology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The **Academy Awards**, more commonly known as the **Oscars**, are awards based on artistic and technical merit in film.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] They are presented annually by the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS) in the United States in recognition of excellence in cinematic achievements, as assessed by the Academy's voting membership.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Oscars are widely considered to be the most prestigious awards in the U.S. film industry, predominantly centered around films produced in Hollywood.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The major award categories, known as the **Academy Awards of Merit**, are presented during a live televised Hollywood ceremony in February or March.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] It is the longest running worldwide entertainment awards ceremony.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The 1st Academy Awards were held in 1929.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The second ceremony, in 1930, was the first to be broadcast by radio, and the 1953 ceremony was the first to be televised.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] It is the oldest of the four major annual American entertainment awards.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Its counterparts — the Emmy Awards for television, the Tony Awards for Broadway theatre, and the Grammy Awards for music — are modeled after the Academy Awards.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Oscar statuette depicts a knight, rendered in the Art Deco style.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The first Academy Awards presentation was held on May 16, 1929 at a private dinner function at the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel, with an audience of about 270 people.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The post-awards party was held at the Mayfair Hotel.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The cost of guest tickets for that night's ceremony was $5 (equivalent to $94 in 2025).
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Fifteen statuettes were awarded, honoring artists, directors, and other participants in the film-making industry of the time, for their works during the 1927–28 period.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] For this first ceremony, winners were announced to the media three months earlier.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] For the second ceremony in 1930, and the rest of the first decade, the results were given to newspapers for publication at 11:00 pm on the night of the awards.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 1940, the *Los Angeles Times* announced the winners before the ceremony began.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] As a result, in 1941 the Academy started using a sealed envelope to reveal the names of the winners.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The term "Oscar" is a registered trademark of the AMPAS.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Historically, the Oscars had been the prime example of glamor in the United States; however, a movement away from both network television and award shows has led to the shift of the focus of glamor from the Oscars to the Met Gala.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Oscars have suffered declining network television ratings and will be moving to YouTube in 2029.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The first Best Actor awarded was Emil Jannings, for his performances in *The Last Command* and *The Way of All Flesh*.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] As he had to return to Europe before the ceremony, the Academy agreed to give him the prize early, making him the first Academy Award recipient.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] For the first Awards, winners were recognized for multiple films during the qualifying period; Jannings received the award for two films in which he starred, and Janet Gaynor won the first Best Actress award for performances in three films.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Beginning with the second ceremony, performers received separate nominations for individual films; no performer has received multiple nominations in the same category since the 3rd Academy Awards.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] For the first five ceremonies, the eligibility period ran from August 1 to July 31.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Best Foreign Language Film, now known as Best International Feature Film, was introduced at the 20th Academy Awards as a special award, and became a competitive category at the 29th Academy Awards.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The 74th Academy Awards, held in 2002, presented the first Academy Award for Best Animated Feature, won by *Shrek*.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Since 1973, all Academy Awards ceremonies, except for 2021, have ended with the Academy Award for Best Picture.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Traditionally, the winners of the acting categories will present an award at the following year's ceremony.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The previous year's winners for Best Actor and Best Supporting Actor present the awards for Best Actress and Best Supporting Actress, respectively, and vice versa.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2009, this model was replaced by each acting award being introduced by five previous winners, each of whom introduces one of the nominated performances, referred to as the "Fab 5" presenters format.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Fab 5 model returned in 2024 after a 15-year hiatus.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] On February 9, 2020, *Parasite* became the first foreign-language film to win Best Picture at the 92nd Academy Awards.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The 93rd Academy Awards ceremony, honoring the best films of 2020 and early 2021, was held on April 25, 2021, after it was postponed from its original February 28, 2021, schedule due to the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on cinema.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] As with the two previous ceremonies, there was no host.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] It took place at the Dolby Theatre in Los Angeles, California for the 19th consecutive year, with satellite locations at Union Station also in Los Angeles.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Because of the virus impact on films and TV industries, Academy president David Rubin and CEO Dawn Hudson announced that for the 2021 Oscar Ceremony, streaming films with a previously planned theatrical release were eligible.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The theatrical requirement was reinstated starting with the 95th Academy Awards.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Oscar statuette, officially the Academy Award of Merit, is given to winners of each year's awards.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Made of gold-plated bronze on a black metal base, it is 13.5 in (34.3 cm) tall, weighs 8.5 lb (3.9 kg) and depicts a knight rendered in Art Deco style holding a sword standing on a reel of film with five spokes.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The five spokes represent the original branches of the Academy: Actors, Writers, Directors, Producers, and Technicians.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Sculptor George Stanley, who also did the Muse Fountain at the Hollywood Bowl, sculpted Cedric Gibbons' design.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The statuettes presented at the initial ceremonies were gold-plated solid bronze.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Within a few years, the bronze was abandoned in favor of Britannia metal, a pewter-like alloy that is then plated in copper, nickel silver, and finally, 24-karat gold.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Due to a metal shortage during World War II, Oscars were made of painted plaster for three years.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Following the war, the Academy invited recipients to redeem the plaster figures for gold-plated metal ones.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The only addition to the Oscar since it was created is a minor streamlining of the base.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The original Oscar mold was cast in 1928 at the C.W.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Shumway & Sons Foundry in Batavia, Illinois, which also contributed to casting the molds for the Vince Lombardi Trophy and Emmy Award statuettes.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] From 1972 to 1986, the Oscar statues were cast at the Dodge Trophy Company in Crystal Lake, Illinois.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] From 1987 to 2015, approximately 50 Oscars in a tin alloy with gold plating were made each year in Chicago by Illinois manufacturer R.S.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] It would take between three and four weeks to manufacture 50 statuettes.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2016, the Academy returned to bronze as the core metal of the statuettes, handing manufacturing duties to Walden, New York-based Polich Tallix Fine Art Foundry, now owned and operated by UAP Urban Art Projects.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] While based on a digital scan of an original 1929 Oscar, the statuettes retain their modern-era dimensions and black pedestal.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Cast in liquid bronze from 3D-printed ceramic molds and polished, they are then electroplated in 24-karat gold by Brooklyn, New York-based Epner Technology.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The time required to produce 50 such statuettes is roughly three months.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Owens is expected to continue producing other awards for the Academy, and service existing Oscars that need replating.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The origin of the nickname of the trophy has been disputed, as multiple people have taken credit for naming the trophy "Oscar".
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Margaret Herrick, librarian and president of the Academy, may have said she named it after her supposed uncle Oscar in 1931.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The only corroboration was a 1938 clipping from the *Los Angeles Examiner*, in which Herrick told a story of her and her husband joking with each other using the phrase, "How's your uncle Oscar".
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Bette Davis, in her 1962 autobiography, claimed she named it in 1936 after her first husband, Harmon Oscar Nelson, of whom the statue's rear end reminded her.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] But the term had been in use at least two years before.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] But in the newspaper clipping that Skolsky referred to, he wrote that "these statues are called 'Oscars'", meaning that the name was already in use.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2021, Brazilian researcher Waldemar Dalenogare Neto contradicted Skolsky's claim to have used the term first, finding the probable first public mention of the name "Oscar" in journalist Relman Morin's "Cinematters" column in the *Los Angeles Evening Record* on December 5, 1933.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Since the awards did not take place that year, he said: "What's happened to the annual Academy banquet?
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Bruce Davis, a former executive director of the Academy, credited Eleanore Lilleberg, a secretary at the Academy when the award was first introduced, for the nickname.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] She had overseen the pre-ceremony handling of the awards.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Davis credits Lilleberg because he found in an autobiography of Einar Lilleberg, Eleanore's brother, that Einar had referenced a Norwegian army veteran named Oscar whom the two knew in Chicago, whom Einar described as having always "stood straight and tall".
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] He asserts credit "should almost certainly belong to" Lilleberg.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] To prevent information identifying the Oscar winners from leaking ahead of the ceremony, Oscar statuettes presented at the ceremony have blank baseplates.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Until 2010, winners returned their statuettes to the Academy and had to wait several weeks to have their names inscribed on their respective Oscars.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Since 2010, winners have had the option of having engraved nameplates applied to their statuettes at an inscription-processing station at the Governor's Ball, a party held immediately after the Oscar ceremony.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Owens company has engraved nameplates made before the ceremony, bearing the name of every potential winner.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The nameplates for the non-winning nominees are later recycled.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Before 1950, Oscar statuettes were, and remain, the property of the recipient.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Since then the statuettes have been legally encumbered by the requirement that the statuette be first offered for sale back to the Academy for $1.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] If a winner refuses to agree to this stipulation, then the Academy keeps the statuette.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Academy Awards predating this agreement have been sold in public auctions and private deals for six-figure sums.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 1989, Michael Todd's grandson tried to sell Todd's Best Picture Oscar for his 1956 production of *Around the World in 80 Days* to a movie prop collector.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Academy earned enforcement of its statuette contract by gaining a permanent injunction against the sale.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 1992, Harold Russell consigned his 1946 Oscar for Best Supporting Actor for *The Best Years of Our Lives* to auction to raise money for his wife's medical expenses.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Though his decision caused controversy, the first Oscar ever to be sold passed to a private collector on August 6, 1992, for $60,500 (equivalent to $138,804 in 2025).
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Russell defended his action, saying, "I don't know why anybody would be critical.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] My wife's health is much more important than sentimental reasons.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The movie will be here, even if Oscar isn't".
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In December 2011, Orson Welles' 1941 Oscar for *Citizen Kane* (Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay) was put up for auction, after his heirs won a 2004 court decision contending that Welles did not sign any agreement to return the statue to the Academy.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Some buyers have subsequently returned the statuettes to the Academy, which keeps them in its treasury.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Academy also awards Nicholl Fellowships in Screenwriting.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] From 2004 to 2020, the Academy Award nomination results were announced to the public in mid-January.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Prior to that, the results were announced in early February.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2021, the nominees were announced in March.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2022, the nominees were announced in early February for the first time since 2003.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS), a professional honorary organization, is composed of 9,905 voting members as of 2024.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Academy membership is divided into different branches, with each representing a different discipline in film production.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] As of 2024, actors constitute the largest bloc, numbering 1,258 (12.7% of the voting body).
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Votes have been certified by the auditing firm PricewaterhouseCoopers, and its predecessor Price Waterhouse, since the 7th Academy Awards in 1935.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In May 2011, the Academy sent a letter advising its then-6,000 or so voting members that an online system for Oscar voting would be implemented in 2013, replacing mailed paper ballots.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] All AMPAS members must be invited to join by the Board of Governors, on behalf of Academy Branch Executive Committees.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Membership eligibility may be achieved by a competitive nomination, or an existing member may submit a name, based on other significant contributions to the field of motion pictures.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] New membership proposals are considered annually.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Academy does not publicly disclose its membership, although as recently as 2007 press releases have announced the names of those who have been invited to join.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2012, the results of a study conducted by the *Los Angeles Times* were published describing the demographic breakdown of approximately 88% of AMPAS' voting membership.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Of the 5,100+ active voters confirmed, 94% were Caucasian, 77% were male, and 54% were found to be over the age of 60.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Thirty-three percent of voting members are former nominees (14%) and winners (19%).
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2016, the Academy launched an initiative to expand its membership and increase diversity.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2024, voting membership stood at 9,905.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2025, a newly announced procedure required Academy members to view all nominated films within a category to be eligible to cast a vote in the final round of that category.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The verification process will be done through the Academy's members-only streaming platform and submitting a form for films viewed at in-person events such as at festivals, screenings or private events.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The film must be shown at least three times on each day of its qualifying run, with at least one of the daily showings starting between 6 pm and 10 pm local time.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] For example, the 2009 Best Picture winner, *The Hurt Locker*, was originally first released in 2008, but did not qualify for the 2008 awards, as it did not play its Oscar-qualifying run in Los Angeles until mid-2009, thus qualifying for the 2009 awards.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Foreign films must include English subtitles.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Each country can submit only one film for consideration in the International Feature Film category per year.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Rule 2 states that a film must be feature-length, defined as a minimum of 40 minutes, except for short-subject awards.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] It must exist either on a 35 mm or 70 mm film print, or in 24 frame/s or 48 frame/s progressive scan digital cinema format, with a minimum projector resolution of 2,048 by 1,080 pixels.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Since the 90th Academy Awards, presented in 2018, multi-part and limited series have been ineligible for the Best Documentary Feature award.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] This followed the win of *O.J.: Made in America*, an eight-hour presentation that was screened in a limited release before being broadcast in five parts on ABC and ESPN, in that category in 2017.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Academy's announcement of the new rule made no direct mention of that film.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Best International Feature Film award does not require a U.S. release.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] It requires the film to be submitted as its country's official selection.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The qualifying theatrical runs must meet the same requirements as those for non-documentary films regarding numbers and times of screenings.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] A film must have been reviewed by a critic from *The New York Times*, *Time Out New York*, the *Los Angeles Times*, or *LA Weekly*.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Producers must submit an Official Screen Credits online form before the deadline.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] If it is not submitted by the defined deadline, the film will be ineligible for Academy Awards in any year.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The form includes the production credits for all related categories.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Awards in short film categories (Best Documentary Short Subject, Best Animated Short Film, and Best Live Action Short Film) have different eligibility rules from most other competitive awards.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] First, the qualifying period for release does not coincide with a calendar year, instead covering one year starting on October 1, and ending on September 30 of the calendar year before the ceremony.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Second, there are multiple methods of qualification.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The main method is a week-long theatrical release in *either* New York City *or* Los Angeles County during the eligibility period.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Films can also qualify by winning specified awards at one of several competitive film festivals designated by the Academy, also without regard to prior public distribution.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] A film that is selected as a gold, silver, or bronze medal winner in an appropriate category of the immediately previous Student Academy Awards is also eligible (Documentary category for that award, and Animation, Narrative, Alternative, or International for the other awards).
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The requirements for the qualifying theatrical run are also different from those for other awards.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] For the Documentary award, the screening must start between noon and 10 pm local time.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] For other awards, no specific start time is required, but the film must appear in regular theater listings with dates and screening times.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In late December, ballots and lists of eligible films are sent to the membership.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] For most categories, members from each of the branches vote to determine the nominees only in their respective categories, i.e. only directors vote for directors, writers for writers, actors for actors, etc.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In the special case of Best Picture, all voting members are eligible to select the nominees.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] A number of branches are only eligible to vote in Best Picture during nomination voting; this includes a producers' branch, as Best Picture is awarded to a film's producer(s), and other branches which have no corresponding award.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In all major categories, a variant of the single transferable vote is used, with each member casting a ballot with up to five nominees (ten for Best Picture) ranked preferentially.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In certain categories, including International Feature Film, Documentary and Animated Feature, nominees are selected by special screening committees made up of members from all branches.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In most categories, the winner is selected from among the nominees by plurality voting of all members.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Since 2009, the Best Picture winner has been chosen by instant-runoff voting.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Since 2013, re-weighted range voting has been used to select the nominees for the Best Visual Effects.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Film companies will spend as much as several million dollars on marketing to awards voters for a film in the running for Best Picture, in attempts to improve chances of receiving Oscars and other film awards conferred in Oscar season.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Academy enforces rules to limit overt campaigning by its members to try to eliminate excesses and prevent the process from becoming undignified.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] It has an awards czar on staff who advises members on allowed practices and levies penalties on offenders.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] For example, a producer of the 2009 Best Picture nominee *The Hurt Locker* was disqualified as a producer in the category when he contacted associates urging them to vote for his film and not another that was seen as the front-runner.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] For the 99th Academy Awards (2027) and thereafter, AMPAS announced on May 1, 2026, its planned rules of eligibility.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Actors and scripts generated by artificial intelligence (AI) will be excluded from acting and screenwriting categories, but human actors rendered by AI will be reviewed at discretion.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Another rule change will expand eligibility of international films by allowing films that won eligible qualifying awards at film festivals, like the Palme d'Or (Cannes), the Golden Lion (Venice), and the Platform Prize (Toronto).
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Another new rule will allow an actor to be nominated more than once in a same acting category of the year.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Another rule change will clarify eligibility of the Best Original Song category: to be eligible, a first song played as the "first music cue" of the end credits must be heard in at least the film's last fifteen seconds until the end credits start.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Academy Screening Room or Academy Digital Screening Room is a secure streaming platform which allows voting members of the Academy to view all eligible films in one place.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] It was introduced in 2019, for the 2020 Oscars.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] DVD screeners and Academy in-person screenings were still provided.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] For films to be included on the platform, the North American distributor must pay $12,500, including a watermarking fee, and a digital copy of the film to be prepared for streaming by the Academy.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The platform can be accessed via Apple TV and Roku players.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The watermarking process involved several video security firms, creating a forensic watermark and restricting the ability to take screenshots or screen recordings.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2021, for the 2022 Oscars, the Academy banned all physical screeners and in-person screenings, restricting official membership viewing to the Academy Screening Room.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Films eligible in the Documentary and International categories were made available in different sections of the platform.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Distributors can also pay an extra fee to add video featurettes to promote their films on the platform.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The in-person screenings were cancelled because of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Eligible films do not have to be added to the platform, but the Academy advertises them to voting members when they are.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The major awards are presented at a live televised ceremony, commonly in late February or early March following the relevant calendar year, and six weeks after the announcement of the nominees.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] It is the culmination of the film awards season, which usually begins during November or December of the previous year.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] This is an elaborate extravaganza, with the invited guests walking up the red carpet in the creations of the most prominent fashion designers of the day.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Black tie dress is the most common outfit for men.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Fashion may dictate not wearing a bow tie, and musical performers are sometimes not required to adhere to this.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The artists who recorded the nominees for Best Original Song quite often perform those songs live at the awards ceremony, and the fact that they are performing is often used to promote the television broadcast.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Academy Awards is the world's longest-running awards show televised live from the United States to all time zones in North America and worldwide, and gathers millions of viewers elsewhere throughout the world.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Oscars were first televised in 1953 by NBC, which continued to broadcast the event until 1960, when ABC took over, televising the festivities, including the first color broadcast of the event in 1966, to 1970.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] NBC regained the rights for five years (1971–75), then ABC resumed broadcast duties in 1976 and its current contract with the Academy runs through 2028, after which the ceremony will be broadcast exclusively on YouTube starting with 2029's ceremony.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Academy has produced condensed versions of the ceremony for broadcast in international markets, especially those outside of the Americas, in more desirable local timeslots.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The ceremony was broadcast live internationally for the first time via satellite since 1970, but only two South American countries, Chile and Brazil, purchased the rights to air the broadcast.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] By that time, the television rights to the Academy Awards had been sold in 50 countries.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 1980, the rights were sold to 60 countries, and by 1984, the television rights to the Academy Awards were licensed in 76 countries.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2004, the ceremonies were moved up from late March/early April to late February, to help disrupt and shorten the intense lobbying and ad campaigns associated with Oscar season in the film industry.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Another reason was because of the growing television ratings success coinciding with the NCAA division I men's basketball tournament, which would cut into the Academy Awards audience.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 1976 and 1977, ABC's regained Oscars were moved from Tuesday to Monday and went directly opposite the national championship game on NBC.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The earlier date is also to the advantage of ABC, as it now usually occurs during the highly profitable and important February sweeps period.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Some years, the ceremony is moved into the first Sunday of March to avoid a clash with the Winter Olympics.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Another reason for the move to late February and early March is to avoid the awards ceremony occurring so close to the religious holidays of Passover and Easter, which for decades had been a grievance from members and the general public.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Advertising is somewhat restricted, as traditionally no film studios or competitors of official Academy Award sponsors may advertise during the telecast.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] As of 2020, the production of the Academy Awards telecast held the distinction of winning one the highest number of Emmys in history, with 54 wins and 280 nominations overall.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] After many years of being held on Mondays at 6:00 p.m.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Eastern, since the 1999 ceremony, it was moved to Sundays at 5:30 p.m.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The reasons given for the move were that more viewers would tune in on Sundays, that Los Angeles rush-hour traffic jams could be avoided, and an earlier start time would prevent the ceremony from going late into the night in the East.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] For many years the film industry opposed a Sunday broadcast because it would cut into the weekend box office.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2010, the Academy contemplated moving the ceremony even further back into January, citing television viewers' fatigue with the film industry's long awards season.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] However, such an accelerated schedule would dramatically decrease the voting period for its members, to the point where some voters would only have time to view the contending films streamed on their computers, as opposed to traditionally receiving the films and ballots in the mail.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Additionally, a January ceremony on Sunday would clash with National Football League (NFL) playoff games.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2018, the Academy announced that the ceremony would be moved from late February to mid-February beginning with the 92nd Academy Awards in 2020.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2024, the ceremony was moved to an even earlier start time of 4:00 p.m.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] ET, in an effort to improve East Coast viewership by having it conclude within primetime hours.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The change also gave the ability for ABC to air a half-hour of primetime programming as a lead-out program at 7:30 p.m.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] ET, after having sometimes done so in the late-night block following late local newscasts.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Originally scheduled for April 8, 1968, the 40th Academy Awards ceremony was postponed for two days, because of the assassination of Dr.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] On March 30, 1981, the 53rd Academy Awards was postponed for one day, after the attempted assassination of President Ronald Reagan and others in Washington, D.C.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 1993, an *In Memoriam* segment was introduced, honoring those who had made a significant contribution to cinema who had died in the preceding 12 months, a selection compiled by a small committee of Academy members.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] This segment has drawn criticism over the years for the omission of some names.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Criticism was also levied for many years regarding another aspect, with the segment having a "popularity contest" feel as the audience varied their applause to those who had died by the subject's cultural impact.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The applause has since been muted during the telecast, and the audience is discouraged from clapping during the segment and giving silent reflection instead.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] This segment was later followed by a commercial break.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In terms of broadcast length, the ceremony generally averages three and a half hours.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The first Oscars, in 1929, lasted 15 minutes.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] At the other end of the spectrum, the 2002 ceremony lasted four hours and twenty-three minutes.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2010, the organizers of the Academy Awards announced winners' acceptance speeches must not run past 45 seconds.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] This, according to organizer Bill Mechanic, was to ensure the elimination of what he termed "the single most hated thing on the show"—overly long and embarrassing displays of emotion.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2016, in a further effort to streamline speeches, winners' dedications were displayed on an on-screen ticker.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] During the 2018 ceremony, host Jimmy Kimmel acknowledged how long the ceremony had become, by announcing that he would give a brand-new jet ski to whoever gave the shortest speech of the night, a reward won by Mark Bridges when accepting his Best Costume Design award for *Phantom Thread*.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Although still dominant in ratings, the viewership of the Academy Awards has steadily dropped.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The 88th Academy Awards were the lowest-rated in the past eight years (although with increases in male and 18–49 viewership), while the show itself also faced mixed reception.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Following the show, *Variety* reported that ABC was, in negotiating an extension to its contract to broadcast the Oscars, seeking to have more creative control over the broadcast itself.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Currently and nominally, AMPAS is responsible for most aspects of the telecast, including the choice of production staff and hosting, although ABC is allowed to have some input on their decisions.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In August 2016, AMPAS extended its contract with ABC to 2028: the contract neither contains any notable changes nor gives ABC any further creative control over the telecast.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] On December 17, 2025, the Academy announced that YouTube had acquired the rights to the Academy Awards beginning with the 101st ceremony in 2029, replacing ABC under a contract that will last through 2033.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] YouTube will serve as the exclusive worldwide broadcaster of the ceremony, while the Oscars' YouTube channel will also feature other AMPAS-produced ancillary content and events (including ceremonies, interviews, and other digital content).
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Academy will also partner with the Google Arts & Culture program to help digitize portions of the Academy Museum of Motion Pictures and the organization's collection.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Historically, the telecast's viewership is higher when box-office hits are favored to win the Best Picture award.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] More than 57.25 million viewers tuned to the telecast for the 70th Academy Awards in 1998, the year of *Titanic*, which generated a box office haul during its initial 1997–98 run of $600.8 million in the US, a box-office record that would remain unsurpassed for years.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The 76th Academy Awards ceremony, in which *The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King* (pre-telecast box office earnings of $368 million) received 11 Awards, including Best Picture, drew 43.56 million viewers.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The most-watched ceremony based on Nielsen ratings to date, was the 42nd Academy Awards (Best Picture *Midnight Cowboy*), which drew a 43.4% household rating on April 7, 1970.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Hoping to reinvigorate the pre-show and ratings, the 2023 Oscars organizers hired members of the Met Gala creative team.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] By contrast, ceremonies honoring films that have not performed well at the box office tend to show weaker ratings, despite how much critical acclaim those films have received.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The 78th Academy Awards, which awarded a low-budget independent film (*Crash* with a pre-Oscar gross of $53.4 million) generated an audience of 38.64 million with a household rating of 22.91%.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2008, the 80th Academy Awards telecast was watched by 31.76 million viewers on average with an 18.66% household rating, the lowest-rated and least-watched ceremony at the time, in spite of celebrating 80 years of the Academy Awards.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Best Picture winner of that particular ceremony was another independent film (this time, the Coen brothers's *No Country for Old Men*).
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Whereas the 92nd Academy Awards drew an average of 23.6 million viewers, the 93rd Academy Awards drew an even lower viewership of 10.4 million, the lowest viewership recorded by Nielsen since it started recording audience totals in 1974.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The 94th and 95th editions drew 16.6 and 18.7 million viewers, respectively, still below the audience of the 92nd edition.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Academy Film Archive holds copies of every Academy Awards ceremony since the 1949 Oscars, as well as material on many prior ceremonies, along with ancillary material related to more recent shows.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Copies are held in a variety of film, video and digital formats.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 1929, the first Academy Awards were presented at a banquet dinner at the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] From 1930 to 1943, the ceremony alternated between two venues: the Ambassador Hotel on Wilshire Boulevard and the Biltmore Hotel in downtown Los Angeles.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Grauman's Chinese Theatre in Hollywood then hosted the awards from 1944 to 1946, followed by the Shrine Auditorium in Los Angeles from 1947 to 1948.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The 21st Academy Awards in 1949 were held at the Academy Award Theatre at what had been the Academy's headquarters on Melrose Avenue in Hollywood.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] From 1950 to 1960, the awards were presented at Hollywood's Pantages Theatre.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] With the advent of television, the awards from 1953 to 1957 took place simultaneously in Hollywood and New York, first at the NBC International Theatre (1953) and the Center Theater (1954), then at the NBC Century Theatre, after which the ceremony took place solely in Los Angeles.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 1961, the Oscars moved to the Santa Monica Civic Auditorium in Santa Monica, California.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 1969, the Academy moved the ceremonies back to Downtown Los Angeles, to the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion at the Los Angeles County Music Center.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In the late 1990s and early 2000s, the ceremony returned to the Shrine Auditorium.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In 2002, Hollywood's Dolby Theatre, previously known as the Kodak Theatre, became the presentation's current venue.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In March 2026, it was announced that the ceremony would relocate to the Peacock Theater beginning in 2029, under a ten-year deal with the venue.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In the first year of the awards, the Best Directing award was split into two categories, Drama and Comedy.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] At times, the Best Original Score award has also been split into separate categories, Drama and Comedy/Musical.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] From the 1930s to the 1960s, the Art Direction (now Production Design), Cinematography, and Costume Design awards were split into two categories (black-and-white films and color films).
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Prior to 2012, the Production Design award was called Art Direction, while the Makeup and Hairstyling award was called Makeup.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Prior to 2020, the International Feature Film award was called Foreign Language Film.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In August 2018, the Academy announced that several categories would not be televised live, but recorded during commercial breaks and aired later in the ceremony.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] Following dissent from Academy members, they announced that they would air all 24 categories live.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] This followed several proposals, among them, the introduction of a Popular Film category, that the Academy had announced but did not implement.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In February 2024, the Academy announced it would introduce an award for Achievement in Casting from the 98th ceremony in 2026, having rejected the category in 1999.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] In April 2025, it announced that Best Stunt Design would be introduced from the 100th ceremony in 2028, having rejected the proposal for a Best Stunt Coordination award every year from 1991 to 2012.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] The Special Academy Awards are voted on by special committees, rather than by the Academy membership as a whole.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p01] They are not always presented on an annual basis.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Due to the positive exposure and prestige of the Academy Awards, many studios spend around 25 million dollars and hire publicists specifically to promote their films during what is typically called the "Oscar season".
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] This has generated accusations of the Academy Awards being influenced more by marketing and lobbying than by quality.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] William Friedkin, an Academy Award-winning film director and former producer of the ceremony, expressed this sentiment at a conference in New York in 2009, describing it as "the greatest promotion scheme that any industry ever devised for itself".
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] A recent technique that has been claimed to be used during the Oscar season is the whisper campaign.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] These campaigns are intended to spread negative perceptions of other films nominated and are believed to be perpetrated by those who were involved in creating the film.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Examples of whisper campaigns include the allegations against *Zero Dark Thirty* suggesting that it justifies torture and the claim that *Lincoln* distorts history.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] This technique was widely used by former producer Harvey Weinstein and his company Miramax, with the campaign strategy gaining further attention after Miramax's *Shakespeare in Love* defeated rival film *Saving Private Ryan* for Best Picture.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] The Oscars have been infamously known for selecting specific genres of films to be awarded.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] The term "Oscar bait" was coined to describe such films.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] This has led, at times, to more specific criticisms that the Academy is disconnected from the audience, e.g., by favoring "Oscar bait" over audience favorites or favoring historical melodramas over critically acclaimed films that depict current life issues.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Despite the success of *The Dark Knight* and *WALL-E*, these films did not receive a Best Picture nomination at the 81st Academy Awards.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] These decisions received substantial criticism and were described as "snubs" by many publications.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] The backlash to the decision was such that, for the 82nd Academy Awards in 2010, the Academy increased the limit for Best Picture nominees from five to ten.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] The Academy Awards have long received criticism over their lack of diversity among the nominees.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] This criticism is based on the statistics from every Academy Awards since 1929, which show that only 6.4% of Academy Award nominees have been non-white and since 1991, 11.2% of nominees have been non-white, with the rate of winners being even more polarizing.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] For a variety of reasons, including marketability and historical bans on interracial couples, a number of high-profile Oscars have been given to yellowface portrayals, as well as performances of Asian characters rewritten for white characters.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] It took until 2023 for an Asian woman to win an Academy Award for Best Actress, when Michelle Yeoh received the award for her performance in *Everything Everywhere All at Once*.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] The 88th awards ceremony became the target of a boycott, popularized on social media with the hashtag #OscarsSoWhite, based on activists' perception that its all-white acting nominee list reflected bias.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] In response, the Academy initiated "historic" changes in membership by 2020.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Some media critics claim the Academy's efforts to address its purported racial, gender and national biases are merely distractions.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] By contrast, the Golden Globe Awards already have multiple winners of Asian descent in leading actress categories.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Some question whether the Academy's definition of "merit" is just or empowering for non-Americans.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] The Academy's Representation and Inclusion Standards have been criticized for excluding Jews as a distinct underrepresented class.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] The Academy has no rules for how to categorize whether a performance is leading or supporting, and it is up to the discretion of the studios whether a given performance is submitted for either Best Actor/Actress or Best Supporting Actor/Actress.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] This has led to situations where a film has two or more co-leads, and one of these is submitted in a supporting category to avoid the two leads competing against each other, and to increase the film's chances of winning.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] This practice has been derisively called "category fraud".
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] For example, Rooney Mara was nominated for Best Supporting Actress for *Carol* (2015), despite her having a comparable amount of screentime to Cate Blanchett, who was nominated for Best Actress.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Another example is *Once Upon a Time in Hollywood* (2019), where Brad Pitt was nominated for and won Best Supporting Actor, even though he played an equally important role to Best Actor nominee Leonardo DiCaprio.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] In both these cases, critics argued that the studios behind the films had placed someone who was actually a leading actor or actress into the supporting categories to avoid them competing against their co-lead.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Following its April 2019 board meeting, the Academy Board of Governors agreed to retain the current rules that allow for streaming media films to be eligible for Oscars as long as they have had limited theatrical runs.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] During the 94th Academy Awards on March 27, 2022, Chris Rock joked about Jada Pinkett Smith's shaved head with a *G.I.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Will Smith walked onstage and slapped Rock across the face, then returned to his seat and told Rock, twice, to "Keep my wife's name out [of] your fucking mouth!" While later accepting the Best Actor award for *King Richard*, Smith apologized to the Academy and the other nominees, but not to Rock.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Rock decided not to press charges against Smith.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] On April 8, 2022, the Academy made an announcement via a letter sent by president David Rubin and CEO Dawn Hudson informing the public that Will Smith had received a ten-year ban from attending the Oscars as a result of the incident.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Some winners critical of the Academy Awards have boycotted the ceremonies and refused to accept their Oscars.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] The first to do so was screenwriter Dudley Nichols (Best Writing in 1935 for *The Informer*).
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Nichols boycotted the 8th Academy Awards ceremony because of conflicts between the Academy and the Writers' Guild.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Nichols eventually accepted the 1935 award three years later, at the 1938 ceremony.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Nichols was nominated for three further Academy Awards during his career.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Scott became the second person to refuse his award (Best Actor in 1970 for *Patton*) at the 43rd Academy Awards ceremony.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Scott described it as a "meat parade", saying, "I don't want any part of it".
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] The third person to refuse the award was Marlon Brando, who refused his award (Best Actor for 1972's *The Godfather*), citing the film industry's discrimination against and mistreatment of Native Americans.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] At the 45th Academy Awards ceremony, Brando asked actress and civil rights activist Sacheen Littlefeather to read a 15-page speech in his place, detailing his criticisms, for which there was booing and cheering by the audience.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] In 2022, Littlefeather was accused by her sisters of misrepresenting her ancestry as Native American.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Adding to the controversy was that the award for Best Animated Short Film (the nominees for which were mostly made up of shorts not aimed at children) was one of the eight categories that were not presented during the live broadcast.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Alberto Mielgo, director of *The Windshield Wiper*, later gave an acceptance speech for the Oscar: "Animation is an art that includes every single art that you can imagine.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] I'm very honored because this is just the beginning of what we can do with animation." Some speculations suggested that the speech played a role in the decision not to broadcast the award.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] The PG-13-rated *The Boy and the Heron* would subsequently win the award.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] It has become a tradition to give out gift bags to the presenters and performers at the Oscars.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] In recent years, these gifts have been extended to award nominees and winners.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] The value of each of these gift bags can reach into the tens of thousands of dollars.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] In 2014, the value was reported to be as high as $80,000.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] The value has risen to the point where the U.S.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Internal Revenue Service issued a statement regarding the gifts and their taxable status.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Some of the gifts have even had a "risque" element to them; in 2014, the adult products retailer Adam & Eve had a "Secret Room Gifting Suite".
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] Celebrities visiting the gifting suite included Judith Hoag, Carolyn Hennesy, Kate Linder, Chris Mulkey, Jim O'Heir and John Salley.
[src:avid-technology/academy-awards-p02] From 2006 onwards, results are Live+SD; all previous years are live viewing.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] As of 2025, AVID operates in more than 7,400 schools across 47 U.S. states and several international locations, including Australia, Canada, and Department of Defense Education Activity (DoDEA) schools.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] Since 2022, Thuan Nguyen is the President and chief executive officer (CEO).
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] AVID began in 1980 at Clairemont High School in San Diego, US.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] Founded by English teacher Mary Catherine Swanson.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] The first elective class had 32 students.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] AVID now serves more than 2 million students in more than 7,500 schools in 47 US states and 16 countries.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] Swanson's work received national recognition in 2001 when she was named one of ''TIME'' magazine's “America’s Best Teachers” and received the Harold W.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] By the early 1990s, AVID expanded beyond San Diego, leading to the creation of AVID Center, a nonprofit organization to manage program dissemination nationwide.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] Over the late 1990s and early 2000s, journalists and researchers began documenting the AVID program and its origins in San Diego.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] AVID subsequently expanded outside the United States.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] Archival sources indicate that by 2001 the program had been adopted in schools in Canada and within the U.S.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] Department of Defense Education Activity (DoDEA) system, alongside continued national growth.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] AVID remains available in both DoDEA Americas and DoDEA Europe schools, including several designated as Schoolwide Sites of Distinction.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] In Australia, AVID was introduced in 2011 through a trial funded by The Victoria Institute at Victoria University.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] In 2015, AVID Center issued Australia an exclusive license to operate the program nationally.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] In 2024, AVID Center approved the establishment of its first international subsidiary in Australia to oversee governance and expand implementation.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] AVID is implemented via school–district partnerships that provide an AVID elective and embed instructional strategies (often summarized as WICOR—Writing, Inquiry, Collaboration, Organization, and Reading) across content areas.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] Department of Defense Education Activity (DoDEA) describes AVID as a framework to strengthen organization, study skills, and access to rigorous coursework in participating schools.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] AVID offers a variety of instructional resources and professional learning programs intended to strengthen college and career readiness in participating schools.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] Its offerings include classroom frameworks, digital learning tools, and educator development pathways that focus on writing, inquiry, collaboration, organization, and reading (WICOR) as core skills for academic success.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] As of 2022, AVID’s chief executive officer is Thuan Nguyen; independent interviews and profiles discuss organizational strategy and professional learning priorities.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] AVID has been recognized by school districts, municipalities, and state governments through official proclamations and observances acknowledging its contributions to education and college readiness.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] AVID Day is an annual observance recognizing AVID educators, students, and alumni.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] It is typically held in September and features classroom activities, community participation, and public reflections on the program’s impact under the theme “Because of AVID, I …”.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] The state of Texas has formally recognized AVID's statewide impact.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] In 2025, the Texas Legislature issued a proclamation honoring AVID's 45-year legacy and designating September 12 as “AVID Day in Texas”.
[src:avid-technology/advancement-via-individual-determination] The proclamation cited AVID's presence in 161 districts and over 1,000 campuses serving more than 200,000 students, noting that 92% of Texas AVID seniors who applied to college were accepted.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Apollo was acquired by Hewlett-Packard in 1989 for US$476 million (equivalent to $1236 million in 2025), and gradually closed down over the period of 1990–1997.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] The brand (as "HP Apollo") was resurrected in 2014 as part of HP's high-performance computing portfolio.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Apollo was started in 1980, two years before rival Sun Microsystems.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] In addition to Poduska, the founders included Dave Nelson (engineering), Mike Greata (engineering), Charlie Spector (COO), Bob Antonuccio (manufacturing), Gerry Stanley (sales and marketing), and Dave Lubrano (finance).
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] The founding engineering team included Mike Sporer, Bernie Stumpf, Russ Barbour, Paul Leach, and Andy Marcuvitz.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Apollo was the first to release a standalone workstation.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] In 1981, the company unveiled the DN100 workstation, which used the Motorola 68000 microprocessor.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Apollo workstations ran Aegis (later replaced by Domain/OS), a proprietary operating system with a Unix alternative shell.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Apollo's networking was particularly elegant, among the first to allow demand paging over the network, and allowing a degree of network transparency and low sysadmin-to-machine ratio.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] From 1980 to 1987, Apollo was the largest manufacturer of network workstations.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Its quarterly sales exceeded $100 million for the first time in late 1986, and by the end of that year, it had the largest worldwide share of the engineering workstations market, at twice the market share of the number two, Sun Microsystems.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] At the end of 1987, it was third in market share after Digital Equipment Corporation and Sun, but ahead of Hewlett-Packard and IBM.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Apollo's largest customers were Mentor Graphics (electronic design), General Motors, Ford, Chrysler, Chicago Research and Trading (Options and Futures) and Boeing.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Apollo was acquired by Hewlett-Packard in 1989 for US$476 million, and gradually closed down over the period 1990–1997.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] But after acquiring Apollo Computer in 1989, HP integrated a lot of Apollo technology into their own HP 9000 series of workstations and servers.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] The Apollo engineering center took over PA-RISC workstation development and Apollo became an HP workstation brand name (*HP Apollo 9000*) for a while.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Apollo also invented the revision control system *DSEE* (Domain Software Engineering Environment) which inspired IBM IBM DevOps Code ClearCase.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Aegis, like Unix, was based on concepts from the Multics time-sharing operating system.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] It used the concepts of shell programming (à la Stephen Bourne), single-level store, and object-oriented design.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Aegis was written in a proprietary version of Pascal.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] The dual 68000 processor configuration was designed to provide automatic page fault switching, with the main processor executing the OS and program instructions, and the "fixer" processor satisfying the page faults.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] When a page fault was raised, the main CPU was halted in mid (memory) cycle while the fixer CPU would bring the page into memory and then allow the main CPU to continue, unaware of the page fault.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Later improvements in the Motorola 68010 processor obviated the need for the dual-processor design.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Certain efficiencies were gained by careful design; for example, the memory page size, network packet, and disk sector were all 1K byte in size.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] With this arrangement, a page fault could take place across the network as well as on the individual computer and Aegis file system was a single system of memory mapped files across the entire network.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] The namespace of the network was self discovering as new nodes (workstations) were added.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Domain/OS (Distributed On-line Multi-access Interactive Network/Operating System) was initially a layer over Aegis and was not built on a Unix kernel.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Release 10 incorporated large parts of Unix but the burden of backwards compatibility with previous releases led to a system that was larger and significantly slower than the previous ones.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] In the end, Hewlett Packard shut down the Domain/OS line.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Release 10 came out as competitors were gaining ground in the area of graphics and windowing systems, particularly with the trend to open systems and the X Window System.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Another feature was its proprietary token ring network, which was originally designed to support relatively small networks of, at most, dozens of computers in an office environment.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] It was a superb design, allowing direct memory access page faulting from any hard drive on the network, but it did not inter-operate with any other existing network hardware or software.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] The industry widely adopted Ethernet and TCP/IP, a more universal, albeit much slower network.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Apollo later added support for these industry standards while continuing to support its own Domain networking using both Ethernet and token ring.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] The Domain network routing was modeled after Xerox Network Systems.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] The company moved from a proprietary data bus architecture in favor of IBM's AT-bus, as used in the second generation of IBM PCs, and was simultaneously embracing RISC technology moving towards high-end processors, eventually producing the PRISM line.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] The workstation industry in general experienced hard times in the second half of the 1980s, as IBM Personal Computers and IBM PC compatibles began making inroads on their customer base.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Thomas Vanderslice was hired as President and CEO in 1984, and founder William Poduska left the company in 1985 to found Stellar.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] The company incurred large losses in 1987 in currency speculation due to the trading activities of one individual, and in 1988 from declining demand for its products.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] In 1989, Apollo was acquired by Hewlett-Packard for US$476 million (equivalent to $1236 million in 2025).
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] HP support for Apollo products was fragmented for the first few years, but was reorganized in late 1992, at which point there were still some 100,000 users of Apollo products and the user group InterWorks had some 4,500 members.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Earlier that year, Sun had already offered discounts on its systems for customers trading in their Apollo machines; HP responded the next winter with a trade-in program of its own, that also allowed trading in hardware from Sun and other vendors in return for a discount on HP workstations.
[src:avid-technology/apollo-computer] Apollo was gradually closed down over the period of 1990–1997.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The **Macintosh II** is a personal computer designed, manufactured, and sold by Apple Computer from March 1987 to January 1990.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Based on the Motorola 68020 32-bit CPU, it is the first Macintosh supporting color graphics.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] When introduced, a basic system with monitor and 20 MB hard drive cost US$5,498 (equivalent to $15,580 in 2025).
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] With a 13-inch color monitor and 8-bit display card, the price was about US$7,145 (equivalent to $20,250 in 2025).
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] This placed it in competition with workstations from Silicon Graphics, Sun Microsystems, and Hewlett-Packard.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The Macintosh II was the first computer in the Macintosh line without a built-in display; a monitor rested on top of the case like the IBM Personal Computer and Amiga 1000.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] It was designed by hardware engineers Michael Dhuey (computer) and Brian Berkeley (monitor) and industrial designer Hartmut Esslinger (case).
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Eighteen months after its introduction, the Macintosh II was updated with a more powerful CPU and sold as the Macintosh IIx.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] In early 1989, the more compact Macintosh IIcx was introduced at a price similar to the original Macintosh II, and by the beginning of 1990 sales stopped altogether.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Motherboard upgrades to turn a Macintosh II into a IIx or Macintosh IIfx were offered by Apple.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Two common criticisms of the original Macintosh, starting from its introduction in 1984, were the closed architecture and lack of color; rumors of a potential color Macintosh began almost immediately.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Jobs instead wanted higher-resolution monochrome displays such as the ones chosen for his own "BigMac" project begun in 1984 to develop a Macintosh successor.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Initially referred to as "Little Big Mac", the Macintosh II was codenamed "Milwaukee" after Dhuey's hometown, and it later went through a series of new names.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] After Jobs was ousted by Apple in September 1985, the Milwaukee project could proceed openly (while Jobs' own BigMac project was cancelled).
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The Macintosh II was introduced at the AppleWorld 1987 conference in Los Angeles, with low-volume initial shipments starting two months later.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Retailing for US $5,498, the Macintosh II was the first modular Macintosh model, so called because it came in a horizontal desktop case like many IBM PC compatibles of the time.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Previous Macintosh computers use an all-in-one design with a black-and-white CRT.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The Macintosh II has drive bays for an internal hard disk (originally 40 MB or 80 MB) and an optional second floppy disk drive.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Along with the Macintosh SE, it was the first Macintosh to use the Apple Desktop Bus (ADB) introduced with the Apple IIGS for keyboard and mouse connection.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The primary improvement in the Macintosh II was Color QuickDraw in ROM, a color version of the Macintosh graphics routines.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Color QuickDraw can handle any display size, up to 8-bit color depth, and multiple monitors.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Because Color QuickDraw is included in the Macintosh II's ROM and relies on 68020 instructions, earlier systems could not be upgraded to display color.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] In September 1988, shortly before the introduction of the Macintosh IIx, Apple increased the list price of the Macintosh II by roughly 20%.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] AnimEigo notably used the Macintosh II for subtitling their earliest releases, including *MADOX-01*, *Riding Bean*, and *Vampire Princess Miyu*, and Industrial Light & Magic used the Macintosh II for image processing on films such as *The Abyss*.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The Macintosh II is built around the Motorola 68020 processor operating at 16 MHz, teamed with a Motorola 68881 floating-point unit.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The standard memory was 1 megabyte, expandable to 8 MB.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The Mac II had eight 30-pin SIMMs, and memory was installed in groups of four (called "Bank A" and "Bank B").
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The Macintosh II does not have a PMMU installed by default.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Instead, it relies on the memory controller hardware to map the installed memory into a contiguous address space.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] This hardware has the restriction that the address space dedicated to Bank A must be larger than that of Bank B.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Though this memory controller was designed to support 16 Megabyte, 30-pin SIMMs in each available slot (for a total of up to 128 MB of RAM), the original Macintosh II ROMs have problems that limit the amount of RAM that can be installed into each slot to just 8 MB SIMMs.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] MODE32 (originally published by Connectix, and later licensed by Apple) contains a workaround that allows for larger SIMMs to be installed in Bank B if a PMMU is also installed.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] With this configuration, the Macintosh II boot ROMs will believe that the computer has 8 MB or less of RAM installed.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Meanwhile, MODE32 then reprograms the memory controller on the fly to dedicate more address space to Bank A, thus allowing access to the additional memory installed in Bank B.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Since this makes the physical address space discontiguous, the PMMU is then used to remap the address space into a contiguous block.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The Macintosh II includes a graphics card that supports a true-color 16.7-million-color palette and was available in two configurations: 4-bit and 8-bit.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The 4-bit model supports 16 colors on a 640×480 display and 256 colors (8-bit video) on a 512×384 display, which means that VRAM was 256 KB.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The 8-bit model supports 256-color video on a 640×480 display, which means that VRAM was 512 KB in size.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] With an optional RAM upgrade (requiring 120 ns DIP chips), the 4-bit version supports 640×480 in 8-bit color.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The video card does not include hardware acceleration of drawing operations.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] A 5.25-inch 40 MB internal SCSI hard disk was optional, as was a second internal 800 kilobyte 3.5-inch floppy disk drive.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Six NuBus slots were available for expansion (at least one of which had to be used for a graphics card, as the Mac II had no onboard graphics chipset and the OS didn't support headless booting).
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] It is possible to connect as many as six displays to a Macintosh II by filling all of the NuBus slots with graphics cards.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Another option for expansion included the Mac286, which included an Intel 80286 chip and could be used for MS-DOS compatibility.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The original ROMs in the Macintosh II contained a bug that prevented the system from recognizing more than one megabyte of memory address space on a Nubus card.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Every Macintosh II manufactured until approximately November 1987 had this defect.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] This happened because Slot Manager was not 32-bit clean.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Apple offered a well-publicized recall of the faulty ROMs and released a program to test whether a particular Macintosh II had the defect.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] IDT sold MacStation products as complete systems based on the Macintosh II, following up with the MacStation 2 employing the 16 MHz R3000 on its RISC CPU board, with 8 MB of RAM supplied on another NuBus card, upgradable to 16 MB, and supplied with a 160 MB hard drive if desired.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The MacStation 3 upgraded the CPU to either a 20 MHz R3000 coupled with 8 MB of RAM or a 25 MHz R3000 with 16 MB of RAM, with the RAM being located on the CPU board itself, and the board gaining dedicated SCSI and serial input/output ports.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The Unix filesystems accessed by the R3000 were encapsulated in Macintosh files if the host machine's storage were to be used.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Otherwise, storage attached to the dedicated SCSI port could host the Unix filesystem with higher performance.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] With Apple's MacX software running on the host, Unix software utilising the X Window System and the Motif graphical toolkit could be used.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] IDT was an "authorized Apple VAR" in offering the MacStation systems.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The Macintosh II and Macintosh SE were the first Apple computers since the Apple I to be sold without a keyboard.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Instead the customer was offered a choice of the new ADB Apple Keyboard or the Apple Extended Keyboard as a separate purchase.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] Dealers could bundle a third-party keyboard or attempt to upsell a customer to the more expensive (and higher-profit) Extended Keyboard.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The Macintosh II was the first Macintosh to have the Chimes of Death accompany the Sad Mac logo whenever a serious hardware error occurred.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The new extensions featured for the Macintosh II at the time were A/ROSE and Sound Manager.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] The Macintosh II was offered in three configurations.
[src:avid-technology/apple-macintosh-ii] All systems included a mouse and a single 800 KB 3.5-inch floppy disk drive; a Motorola 68851 PMMU was available as an option and required for running A/UX.
[src:avid-technology/aspera-company] Aspera was founded in 2004 by Michelle Munson and Serban Simu.
[src:avid-technology/aspera-company] Munson and Simu patented and Aspera developed FASP, a high-speed data transfer protocol, and software products based on FASP.
[src:avid-technology/aspera-company] Aspera won a 2013 Primetime Engineering Emmy Award for Outstanding Achievement in Engineering Development and a 2014 Technology and Engineering Emmy Award for Secure Accelerated File Movement over IP including the Internet.
[src:avid-technology/aspera-company] The company received a Hollywood Professional Association (HPA) Engineering Excellence Award for its Telestream Vantage with Lightspeed Live Capture product in 2018.
[src:avid-technology/asset] In financial accounting, an **asset** is any resource owned or controlled by a business or an economic entity.
[src:avid-technology/asset] It is anything (tangible or intangible) that can be used to produce positive economic value.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Assets represent value of ownership that can be converted into cash (although cash itself is also considered an asset).
[src:avid-technology/asset] The balance sheet of a firm records the monetary value of the assets owned by that firm.
[src:avid-technology/asset] It covers money and other valuables belonging to an individual or to a business.
[src:avid-technology/asset] *Total assets* can also be called the *balance sheet total*.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Assets can be grouped into two major classes: tangible assets and intangible assets.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Tangible assets contain various subclasses, including current assets and fixed assets.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Current assets include cash, inventory, accounts receivable, while fixed assets include land, buildings and equipment.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Intangible assets are non-physical resources and rights that have a value to the firm because they give the firm an advantage in the marketplace.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Intangible assets include goodwill, intellectual property (such as copyrights, trademarks, patents, computer programs), and financial assets, including financial investments, bonds, and companies' shares.
[src:avid-technology/asset] IFRS (International Financial Reporting Standards), the most widely used financial reporting system, defines: "An asset is a present economic resource controlled by the entity as a result of past events.
[src:avid-technology/asset] E17: An asset has the following two essential characteristics: (a) It is a present right (b) The right is to an economic benefit.
[src:avid-technology/asset] E18:The combination of those two characteristics allows an entity to obtain the economic benefit and control others' access to the benefit.
[src:avid-technology/asset] A present right of an entity to an economic benefit entitles the entity to the economic benefit and the ability to restrict others' access to the benefit to which the entity is entitled.
[src:avid-technology/asset] This accounting definition of assets includes items that are not owned by an enterprise, for example a leased building (Finance lease), but excludes employees because, while they have the capacity to generate economic benefits, an employer cannot control an employee.
[src:avid-technology/asset] In economics, an asset (economics) is any form in which wealth can be held.
[src:avid-technology/asset] There is a growing analytical interest in assets and asset forms in other social sciences too, especially in terms of how a variety of things (e.g., personality, personal data, ecosystems, etc.) can be turned into an asset.
[src:avid-technology/asset] In the financial accounting sense of the term, it is not necessary to have title (a legally enforceable ownership right) to an asset.
[src:avid-technology/asset] An asset may be recognized as long as the reporting entity controls the rights (economic resource) the asset represents.
[src:avid-technology/asset] The essential characteristic of control is the ability to benefit from the asset and prevent other entities from doing likewise.
[src:avid-technology/asset] The IFRS conceptual framework explains (CF 4.20): An entity controls an economic resource if it has the present ability to direct the use of the economic resource and obtain the economic benefits that may flow from it.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Control includes the present ability to prevent other parties from directing the use of the economic resource and from obtaining the economic benefits that may flow from it.
[src:avid-technology/asset] It follows that, if one party controls an economic resource, no other party controls that resource.
[src:avid-technology/asset] The accounting equation is the mathematical structure of the balance sheet.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Assets are reported on the balance sheet.
[src:avid-technology/asset] On the balance sheet, additional sub-classifications are generally required by generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP), which vary from country to country.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Assets can be divided into current and non-current (a.k.a. fixed or long-lived).
[src:avid-technology/asset] Current assets are generally subclassified as cash and cash equivalents, receivables, inventory, and accruals (such as pre-paid expenses).
[src:avid-technology/asset] Non-current assets are generally subclassified as investments (financial instruments), property, plant and equipment, intangible assets (including goodwill) and other assets (such as resources or biological assets).
[src:avid-technology/asset] Current assets are cash and others that are expected to be converted to cash or consumed either in a year or in the operating cycle (whichever is longer), without disturbing the normal operations of a business.
[src:avid-technology/asset] These assets are continually turned over in the course of a business during normal business activity.
[src:avid-technology/asset] **Receivables** – usually reported as net of allowance for non-collectable accounts.
[src:avid-technology/asset] **Inventory** – trading these assets is a normal business of a company.
[src:avid-technology/asset] The inventory value reported on the balance sheet is usually the historical cost or fair market value, whichever is lower.
[src:avid-technology/asset] This is known as the "lower of cost or market" rule.
[src:avid-technology/asset] **Prepaid expenses** – these are expenses paid in cash and recorded as assets before they are used or consumed (common examples are insurance or office supplies).
[src:avid-technology/asset] The phrase *net current assets* (also called *working capital*) is often used and refers to the total of current assets less the total of current liabilities.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Often referred to simply as "investments".
[src:avid-technology/asset] Long-term investments are to be held for many years and are not intended to be disposed of in the near future.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Investments in special funds (e.g. sinking funds or pension funds).
[src:avid-technology/asset] Different forms of insurance may also be treated as long-term investments.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Also referred to as PP&E (property, plant and equipment), these are purchased for continued and long-term use to earn profit in a business.
[src:avid-technology/asset] This group includes land, buildings, machinery, furniture, tools, IT equipment (e.g., laptops, software for long term use *or more than a year* that’s capitalized and amortized), and certain wasting resources (e.g., timberland and minerals).
[src:avid-technology/asset] They are written off against profits over their anticipated life by charging depreciation expenses (with exception of land assets).
[src:avid-technology/asset] Accumulated depreciation is shown in the face of the balance sheet or in the notes.
[src:avid-technology/asset] These are also called capital assets in management accounting.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Companies which invest a significant portion of their capital in assets are sometimes referred to as asset-heavy model companies.
[src:avid-technology/asset] On the other hand, companies which operate with very few or no assets are called light asset model companies.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Sectors such as manufacturing, medical, engineering and chemicals typically operate as heavy asset model businesses, whereas businesses primarily providing digital or intangible services typically operate as light asset model businesses.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Intangible assets lack physical substance and usually are very hard to evaluate.
[src:avid-technology/asset] They include patents, copyrights, franchises & licenses, goodwill, trademarks, trade names, software, etc.
[src:avid-technology/asset] These assets are (according to US GAAP) amortized to expense over 5 to 40 years with the exception of goodwill.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Websites are treated differently in different countries and may fall under either tangible or intangible assets.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Tangible assets are those that have a physical substance, such as currencies, buildings, real estate, vehicles, inventories, equipment, art collections, precious metals, rare-earth metals, Industrial metals, and crops.
[src:avid-technology/asset] The physical health of tangible assets deteriorate over time.
[src:avid-technology/asset] As a result, asset managers use deterioration modeling to predict the future conditions of assets.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Depreciation is applied to tangible assets when those assets have an anticipated lifespan of more than one year.
[src:avid-technology/asset] This process of depreciation is used instead of allocating the entire expense to one year.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Tangible assets such as art, furniture, stamps, gold, wine, toys and books are recognized as an asset class in their own right.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Many high-net-worth individuals will seek to include these tangible assets as part of their overall asset portfolio.
[src:avid-technology/asset] This has created a need for tangible asset managers.
[src:avid-technology/asset] A wasting asset is an asset that irreversibly declines in value over time.
[src:avid-technology/asset] This could include vehicles and machinery, and in financial markets, options contracts that continually lose time value after purchase.
[src:avid-technology/asset] Mines and quarries in use are wasting assets.
[src:avid-technology/asset] An asset classified as wasting may be treated differently for tax and other purposes than one that does not lose value; this may be accounted for by applying depreciation.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The company was founded in 1982 by John Walker, who was a co-author of the first versions of AutoCAD.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] AutoCAD is the company's flagship computer-aided design (CAD) software and, along with its 3D design software Revit, is primarily used by architects, engineers, and structural designers to design, draft, and model buildings and other structures.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk software has been used in many fields, and on projects from the One World Trade Center to Tesla electric cars.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk became best known for AutoCAD, but now develops a broad range of software for design, engineering, and entertainment—and a line of software for consumers.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The manufacturing industry uses Autodesk's digital prototyping software—including Autodesk Inventor, Autodesk Fusion, and the Autodesk Product Design Suite—to visualize, simulate, and analyze real-world performance using a digital model in the design process.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The company's Revit line of software for building information modeling is designed to let users explore the planning, construction, and management of a building virtually before it is built.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk's Media and Entertainment division creates software for visual effects, color grading, and editing as well as animation, game development, and design visualization.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] 3ds Max and Maya are both 3D animation software used in film visual effects and game development.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The company was founded by John Walker, Daniel Drake, and 14 other programmers in April 1982, who invested $60,000.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Walker founded the company after acquiring Interact, a computer-aided design program that operated on microcomputers running the 8-bit CP/M operating system and two of the new 16-bit systems, the Victor 9000 and the IBM Personal Computer (PC).
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] This tool made it affordable for smaller design, engineering, and architecture companies to create detailed technical drawings.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The program had been developed by Michael Riddle in 1979.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Riddle had struggled to sell the program, and agreed to sell it to Walker in exchange for royalties.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The program was further developed and renamed AutoCAD.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The cofounders were unsure of which area of technology to pursue, so founded the company first and planned as many as five different software applications to see which would succeed.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] AutoCAD went on sale in December 1982 and earned $1.4 million in revenue in its first year.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Walker said in December 1984 that Autodesk was profitable from its first month and had not needed loans or outside investors.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] By then the company had about 10,000 AutoCAD systems installed; it was so successful that for a while Autodesk implied that AutoCAD was the company's name.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The company continued to see itself as a general-purpose software company until new CEO Carol Bartz ended diversification outside computer-aided design in the early 1990s.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk became a public company in 1985.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] John Walker did not enjoy the process of writing the prospectus, relating the process to "lying on the beach or juggling chainsaws".
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Release 2.1 of AutoCAD, released in 1986, included AutoLISP, a built-in Lisp programming language interpreter initially based on XLISP.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] This opened the door for third party developers to extend AutoCAD's functionality, to address a wide range of vertical markets, strengthening AutoCAD's market penetration.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Subsequent to AutoCAD Release 13, the company stopped supporting the Unix environment and the Apple Macintosh platform.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] After AutoCAD Release 14 (R13 was last DOS & Unix release), first shipped in 1997, Autodesk discontinued development under DOS, and focused exclusively on Microsoft Windows.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] AutoCAD has grown to become the most widely used CAD program for 2D non-specialized applications.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The native file formats written by AutoCAD, DXF and DWG, are also widely used for CAD data interoperability.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] In 1989, Autodesk's sales grew to over $100,000,000 after just four operational years.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Walker remained a programmer at Autodesk until 1994, when he left due to disagreements with changes at the company.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] With the purchase of Softdesk in 1997, Autodesk started to develop specialty versions of AutoCAD, targeted to broad industry segments, including architecture, civil engineering, and manufacturing.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] In 2007, Timothy Vernor sued Autodesk (*Vernor v.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk, Inc.*), alleging that he was entitled to resell "used" copies of AutoCAD software on eBay.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] He had obtained the software from an Autodesk licensee at an office liquidation sale.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] A federal district judge in Washington denied Autodesk's initial motion to dismiss in early 2008.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] In February and March 2009, both sides filed motions for summary judgment addressing the issue whether the First Sale Doctrine applies to previously licensed software.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] As such, Autodesk could not pursue an action for copyright infringement against Vernor, who sought to resell used versions of its software on eBay.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk appealed the decision to the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit, which reversed the lower court ruling, denying Vernor the right to resale Autodesk software due to Autodesk's nontransferable licensing restrictions.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Supreme Court let stand the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals ruling.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk introduced a new logo at the TED conference in Long Beach, California, on February 26, 2013.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk announced the largest lay off in its history on November 27, 2017, with the lay off of 1,150 jobs.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] This was in addition to the almost 1,000 job cuts announced in January 2016.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The number of Autodesk employees decreased from approximately 9,200 to 7,200 in less than 2 years.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk updated to its current logo in September 2021.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] In 2022, Autodesk moved its headquarters to San Francisco from San Rafael, California—which served as its headquarters since 1994.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] In 2025, Autodesk layoffs of 1,350 employees roughly 9% of its workforce as part of restructuring effort to focus on AI and cloud computing.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] In January 2026, Autodesk shed about 7% of its global workforce.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] This amounted to approximately 1000 jobs.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] In February 2026, Autodesk announced its investment of $200 million in World Labs, an AI spatial intelligence company who specializes in multimodal world models.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The world models developed by World Labs are able to generate realistic 3D worlds that can manipulated, simulated, reconstructed, and interacted with by both human users and AI agents.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk's collaboration with World Labs aims to advance physical-world AI via technical exploration inspired by customer desires and real-world outcomes.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Additionally, World Labs announced their mission to revolutionize storytelling, creativity, robotics, scientific discovery, and more using the new funding and knowledge Autodesk brings.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk will serve as an advisor to World Labs with collaboration in research and world model development.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] According to AutoDesk News, the investment in World Labs is a deliberate choice to pursue a more human centered path when developing and using AI solutions.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The Platform Solutions and Emerging Business (PSEB) division develops and manages the product foundation for most Autodesk offerings across multiple markets, including Autodesk's flagship product AutoCAD, AutoCAD LT, AutoCAD for Mac, and the AutoCAD mobile app (formerly AutoCAD 360).
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk Suites, Subscription and Web Services, which include Autodesk Cloud, Autodesk Labs, and Global Engineering are also part of PSEB.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] In what was seen as an unusual step for a maker of high-end business software, Autodesk began offering AutoCAD LT 2012 for Mac through the App Store.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Also part of PSEB is the Autodesk Consumer Product Group, which was created in November 2010 to generate interest in 3-D design and “foster a new wave of designers who hunger for sophisticated software”.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Users range from children, students and artists to makers and DIYers.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk offers certificates in two categories: Autodesk Certified User and Advanced Certified Professional.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The Architecture, Engineering and Construction (AEC) industry group is headquartered in Boston, Massachusetts, in a LEED Platinum building designed and built using Autodesk software.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk's architecture, engineering, and construction solutions include AutoCAD, and Revit, which is its flagship product for relational Building information modeling.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The Autodesk Services Marketplace offering helps its clients train their team in AEC Industry.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Projects that have used software from the Autodesk AEC division include the NASA Ames building, the San Francisco Bay Bridge, the Shanghai Tower, and New York's One World Trade Center.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk Life Sciences is an extensible toolkit for genetic engineering.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] It visualises DNA code (Molecule Viewer), and has a tool for writing DNA code (genetic constructor).
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The tool allows work on molecule-level, rather than nucleobase-level (A, C, G, T) constructs.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk's manufacturing industry group is headquartered in Portland, Oregon.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The company's manufacturing software is used in various manufacturing segments, including industrial machinery, electro-mechanical, tool and die, industrial equipment, automotive components, and consumer products.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk Media and Entertainment products are designed for digital media creation, management, and delivery, from film and television visual effects, color grading, and editing to animation, game development, and design visualization.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk's Media and Entertainment Division is based in Montreal, Quebec.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] It was established in 1999 after Autodesk, Inc. acquired Discreet Logic, Inc. and merged its operations with Kinetix.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] In January 2006, Autodesk acquired Alias, a developer of 3D graphics technology.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] In October 2008, Autodesk acquired the Softimage brand from Avid.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] The principal product offerings from the Media and Entertainment Division are Flame, Flow Production Tracking, and the Media & Entertainment Collection, which include Maya, 3ds Max, Arnold, MotionBuilder, Mudbox, Golaem, and ReCap Pro.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Much of *Avatar'*s visual effects were created with Autodesk media and entertainment software.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk software enabled *Avatar* director James Cameron to aim a camera at actors wearing motion-capture suits in a studio and see them as characters in the fictional world of Pandora in the film.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk software also played a role in the visual effects of *Alice in Wonderland*, *The Curious Case of Benjamin Button*, *Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows – Part 1*, *Inception*, *Iron Man 2*, *King Kong*, *Gladiator*, *Titanic*, and other films.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Walt Disney Animation Studios also utilizes Autodesk Maya for character rigging and animation, being used in films such as Frozen II.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk develops and purchased many specific-purpose renderers but many Autodesk products had been bundled with third-party renderers such as NVIDIA Mental Ray or Iray.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk CFD (formerly Autodesk Simulation CFD) includes modeling and thermal modeling tools for architectural and MEP applications.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Common applications for environmental sustainable design include mechanical ventilation, external flow (wind loading), natural ventilation, and occupant comfort.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Other energy applications include analysis for building energy, solar load, advanced energy and heating and cooling.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk introduced C-FACT, an open-source, science-driven approach to setting greenhouse gas reduction targets, which calls for greenhouse gas (GHG) reductions to be made in proportion to a company's gross domestic product (GDP).
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Unlike other carbon accounting methods, Autodesk's C-FACT measures carbon dioxide emissions that are proportional to a company's global GDP contribution.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] Autodesk will derive its own targets using this approach through 2020.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] In 2006, Autodesk sponsored a PBS program named *e² Design*, which focused on green building design around the world, describing the leaders and technologies that drive sustainable design.
[src:avid-technology/autodesk] In November 2021, the company was added to the Dow Jones Sustainability World Index.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] Avid was founded in August 1987 by Bill Warner, a former marketing manager from Apollo Computer.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] A prototype of their first non-linear editing system, the Avid/1 Media Composer, was shown at the National Association of Broadcasters (NAB) convention in April 1988.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] The Avid/1 was based on an Apple Macintosh II computer, with special hardware and software of Avid's design installed.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] The Avid/1 was "the biggest shake-up in editing since Melies played with time and sequences in the early 1900s".
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] By the early 1990s, Avid products began to replace such tools as the Moviola, Steenbeck, and KEM flatbed editors, allowing editors to handle their film creations with greater ease.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] The first feature film edited using the Avid was *Let's Kill All the Lawyers* in 1992, directed by Ron Senkowski.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] The film was edited at a 30fps NTSC rate, then used Avid MediaMatch to generate a negative cutlist from the EDL.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] The first feature film edited natively at 24fps with what was to become the Avid Film Composer was *Emerson Park*.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] The first studio film to be edited at 24fps was *Lost in Yonkers*, directed by Martha Coolidge.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] By 1994 only three feature films used the new digital editing system.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] By 1995 dozens had switched to Avid, and it signaled the beginning of the end of cutting celluloid.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] In 1996 Walter Murch accepted the Academy Award for editing *The English Patient* (which also won best picture), which he cut on the Avid.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] This was the first Editing Oscar awarded to a digitally edited film (although the final print was still created with traditional negative cutting).
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] In 1994 Avid introduced Open Media Framework (OMF) as an open standard file format for sharing media and related metadata.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] Over the years, Avid has released numerous freeware versions of Media Composer.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] Initially this included Avid Free DV: a free edition of Media Composer with limited functionality; Avid Xpress DV: a consumer edition of Media Composer; and then Avid Xpress Pro: a prosumer edition of Media Composer.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] These editions were discontinued in 2008 as the flagship Media Composer was lowered in price.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] Later, Avid released Media Composer | First, which included a large portion of Media Composer's functionality but its exporting workflows publishing finished videos directly to web services like YouTube.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] On March 29, 1999, Avid Technology, Inc. adjusted the amount originally allocated to IPR&D and restated its third-quarter 1998 consolidated financial statements accordingly, considering the SEC's views.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] In February 2018, Avid appointed Jeff Rosica as CEO, after terminating Louis Hernandez Jr, who was accused of workplace misconduct.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] In November 2023, Avid Technology was acquired by an affiliate of STG for $1.4 billion.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] This process delisted Avid from the public stock exchange, making it private.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] In April 2024, Avid appointed Wellford Dillard as CEO, succeeding Jeff Rosica.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] 1993: The National Academy of Television Arts & Sciences awarded Avid Technology and all of the company's initial employees with a technical Emmy award for Outstanding Engineering Development for the Avid Media Composer video editing system.
[src:avid-technology/avid-technology] 1999: At the 71st Academy Awards, Avid Technology Inc. was awarded an Oscar for the concept, system design and engineering of the Avid Film Composer for motion picture editing which was accepted by founder Bill Warner.
